title: GlusterFS cluster and volume monitoring

agents: glusterfs

catalog: storage

license: GPL

distribution: check_mk

description:
 This check monitors GlusterFS clusters and volumes.

 It evaluates:
  - Cluster peer connectivity
  - Volume health
  - Brick availability
  - Self-heal activity

 The check creates:
  - One service for the GlusterFS cluster (peer status)
  - One service per volume

item:
 The name of the GlusterFS volume.

inventory:
 A service is created for each detected volume based on the output
 of the GlusterFS agent plugin.

discovery:
 The check automatically discovers:
  - A cluster service (no item)
  - Volume services (items based on "Volume Name")

parameters:
 brick_down_warn:
  Number of bricks that need to be down before the service changes
  to WARNING.

 brick_down_crit:
  Number of bricks that need to be down before the service changes
  to CRITICAL.

 warn_on_heal:
  If enabled, the service will enter WARNING state when GlusterFS
  self-heal activity is detected.

levels:
 The state is determined as follows:

  OK:
   All bricks are up and no heal activity is present.

  WARNING:
   - Number of down bricks >= brick_down_warn
   - OR self-heal activity detected (if enabled)

  CRITICAL:
   - Number of down bricks >= brick_down_crit
   - OR cluster peer is disconnected

perfdata:
 No performance data is currently generated.

 To extend this check, metrics such as:
  - Number of bricks
  - Heal backlog
  - Volume usage
 can be added in future versions.

notes:
 The agent plugin must be installed on the monitored host
 and executable by the Checkmk agent.

 The plugin requires the "gluster" command-line tools
 to be available on the system.

 Ensure the Checkmk agent user has sufficient permissions
 to execute:
   - gluster peer status
   - gluster volume info
   - gluster volume status
   - gluster volume heal

example:
 A healthy volume:
   OK - Volume healthy

 A degraded volume:
   CRIT - 1/4 bricks down

 A healing volume:
   WARN - Self-heal in progress

 A cluster issue:
   CRIT - Peer disconnected